key_contracts.api:
Module constants: LIMIT_UP_RATIO = 1.299 (open >= prev_close*1.299 blocks buy fill), LIMIT_DOWN_RATIO = 0.701 (open <= prev_close*0.701 blocks sell fill, position carried over).

@dataclass BacktestResult: equity: pd.Series (cumulative, (1+daily_ret).cumprod(), name 'equity'); daily_ret: pd.Series (aligned to df.index, name 'daily_ret'); trades: pd.DataFrame (columns entry_date, exit_date, entry_price, exit_price, net_ret, holding_days, open).

def run_backtest(df: pd.DataFrame, signal: pd.Series, cost: KoreaCostModel, stop_pct: float | None = None, take_profit_pct: float | None = None) -> BacktestResult. df needs columns open/high/low/close and DatetimeIndex; signal is {0,1} indexed like df (reindexed+fillna(0) if not). Semantics: desired = signal.shift(1).fillna(0) > 0.5 (day 0 always flat). Entry at open: entry_eff = open*(1+buy_cost), entry-day return = close/entry_eff - 1; entry-day close can already trip stop/TP (exit_pending set at entry). Exit at open: exit_eff = open*(1-sell_cost), exit-day return = exit_eff/prev_close - 1. Hold: close/prev_close - 1. Stop breach: close <= entry_open*(1-stop_pct); TP breach: close >= entry_open*(1+take_profit_pct) — both referenced to RAW entry-day open, force exit at NEXT open, pending exit retries through limit-down locks. After a forced exit, re-entry blocked while shifted signal stays continuously 1; re-arms when it returns to 0. Buy blocked by limit-up retries next day while signal stays on. Position still open at end of data -> TradeRecord with exit_price = last close, net_ret = close[-1]/entry_eff - 1, open=True. Implementation is a per-bar int loop over numpy arrays (open_, close, prev_close = np.concatenate(([nan], close[:-1]))), not fully vectorized — but all inputs/masks are precomputed vectorized.

@dataclass(frozen=True) ParamRange: low: float; high: float; is_int: bool = True; def clamp(value: float) -> float (min/max clamp, int(round()) if is_int).
ParamGrid = dict[str, ParamRange].
@dataclass StrategySpec: template: str; params: dict[str, float] = {}; def id_key() -> str returns 'template(k1=v1,k2=v2)' with params sorted by key and values formatted %g — this string is the strategy's canonical identity used as the signal Series name (and by callers as a champion key).
def signal_from_events(entry: pd.Series, exit_: pd.Series, index: pd.Index) -> pd.Series: stateful {0,1} — NaN series, set 0.0 where exit fires FIRST then 1.0 where entry fires (entry wins same-bar conflicts), ffill().fillna(0.0) (starts flat).
def generate_signal(spec: StrategySpec, df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.Series: looks up registry.SIGNAL_FUNCS[spec.template] (raises ValueError('unknown strategy template: ...') on miss); strips the 'stop' key from params before calling the signal fn (signals stay pure — stop is an execution param read only by engine/trader); returns fn(df, **params).astype(float).rename(spec.id_key()).

@dataclass Quote(ticker: str, price: float, ts: str)  # ts = ISO date string for paper (last cached bar date), ISO datetime for live
@dataclass Position(ticker: str, qty: int, avg_price: float)
@dataclass Balance(cash: float, positions: list[Position] = [])
@dataclass OrderRequest(ticker: str, side: Literal['buy','sell'], qty: int, price: float | None = None)  # price=None means market order
@dataclass Order(id: str, ticker: str, side: str, qty: int, filled_price: float | None, status: Literal['pending','filled','rejected'], reason: str = '')
class Broker(ABC):
    async def get_quote(self, symbol: str) -> Quote
    async def get_balance(self) -> Balance
    async def place_order(self, request: OrderRequest) -> Order
    async def get_orders(self, limit: int = 50) -> list[Order]
# __init__.py re-exports: Balance, Broker, Order, OrderRequest, Position, Quote, PaperBroker

_COLUMNS = ['open','high','low','close','volume']
class DataLoader:
    def __init__(self, db: Database)
    def _today() -> dt.date                      # overridable in tests
    def _last_complete_session() -> dt.date      # most recent weekday strictly before today (holiday = harmless re-fetch)
    def get_ohlcv(ticker: str, years: int = 5) -> pd.DataFrame  # float cols open/high/low/close/volume, normalized (midnight) DatetimeIndex, sorted, deduped (keep='last'), NaN-dropped. Flow: read cache from today-365*years; if cache max date >= last_complete_session return cache as-is; else fetch from (cache_max+1day) or full window, drop rows with index.date >= today (in-progress bar), upsert, then re-read cache (single source of truth for the returned frame)
    def refresh(tickers: list[str]) -> dict[str, int]  # per-ticker newly-cached row count; each ticker's exception is caught+logged so one bad symbol never kills the cycle
    def _fetch(ticker, start) -> pd.DataFrame | None    # FinanceDataReader first; on failure yfinance f'{ticker}.KS' then f'{ticker}.KQ' with auto_adjust=True; all fail → None (cache-only mode)
    @staticmethod _normalize(df) -> pd.DataFrame        # flatten MultiIndex columns (yfinance), lowercase, select _COLUMNS, astype(float), normalize+dedupe+sort index, dropna
    def _upsert(ticker, df)                             # INSERT OR REPLACE INTO ohlcv_cache(ticker, date, o,h,l,c,v) with date as ISO string
# empty result shape: pd.DataFrame(columns=_COLUMNS, index=pd.DatetimeIndex([]))

